                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-defend2244" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18321018-263-off1482" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-off1482" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-off1482" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18321018-263-cd1483" type="crimeDate">13th of October</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18321018-263-off1482 t18321018-263-cd1483"></join>, 16 yards of ribbon, value 3s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               
                  <persName id="t18321018-263-victim2246" type="victimName">
                     John 
                     Udall
                  <interp inst="t18321018-263-victim2246" type="surname" value="Udall"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-victim2246" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-victim2246" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18321018-263-off1482 t18321018-263-victim2246"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>MR. ADOLPHUS conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18321018-263-person2247">
                  ROBERT 
                  UDALL
               <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2247" type="surname" value="UDALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2247" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2247" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am superintendent of my father's business at <placeName id="t18321018-263-crimeloc1484">Edmonton</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18321018-263-crimeloc1484" type="placeName" value="Edmonton"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18321018-263-crimeloc1484" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18321018-263-off1482 t18321018-263-crimeloc1484"></join> - he is a <rs id="t18321018-263-viclabel1485" type="occupation">draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18321018-263-victim2246 t18321018-263-viclabel1485"></join> - his name is John. On the evening of the 13th of October the prisoner came to his shop, and bought a pair of black worsted stockings; there was on the counter a drawer of black ribbons - she did not offer to buy any of them, but when she was gone I received information, and looked over the ribbons, and missed one, which had been safe ten minutes before - I knew the prisoner; she lived in the neighbourhood; I knew that when she left the shop; she had gone the contrary way to her own house, and she must return past the shop - I sent a witness to stop her; I went and asked her into the shop - I saw her drop this ribbon outside the door, on the pavement; I said she had better tell the truth.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. What colour were the stockings? A. Black, and so was the ribbon; there were a good many other ribbons in the drawer, but no other of this width; I put the ribbon back into the drawer - I threw it in - my brother got the constable.</p>
               <p>MR. ADOLPHUS. Q. Did the ribbons and stockings stand so near to one another, that she could take one with the other? A. No; the stockings were in paper, and the ribbon in a drawer; there was no other piece of ribbon in the drawer that I could mistake for this; there is about sixteen yards of it.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did you sell her the stockings? A. Yes, and she had them in herlap when she came back.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18321018-263-person2248">
                  ELIZABETH 
                  FRANKLIN
               <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2248" type="surname" value="FRANKLIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2248" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2248" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in the prosecutor's employ, and was in his shop; the prisoner was at the counter- the stockings were at the end of the counter, in paper, and the ribbons were in a drawer a very little distance from the stockings - I saw the prisoner put her hand into the drawer, take something out, and put it into her lap; I not know what it was.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. How near were the ribbons and stockings? A. A very little distance off - I knew where she lived; there was nothing to prevent her going straight home, but she went a contrary way, and passed our shop again.</p>
               <p>MR. ADOLPHUS. Q. Was there any thing that mixed the stockings with the ribbons, so that one could be taken with the other? A. No; the stockings were on her lefthand side, and the ribbons on the right.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18321018-263-person2249">
                  JOHN 
                  HOCKLEY
               <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2249" type="surname" value="HOCKLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2249" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18321018-263-person2249" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with the prosecutor. I remember the prisoner coming back; she hurled this ribbon from her apron on the pavement, and I took it up.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. What do you mean by hurling it? A. She threw it on the pavement - my master was near her; it could not be seen by every body in the shop.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received an excellent character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 18.</p>
